WEBVTT

1
00:00:06.940 --> 00:00:14.340
Hi everyone, I'm Fabio from Free Wings and today we're going to look at meteorology together.

2
00:00:15.840 --> 00:00:21.430
This is mainly about exam preparation, or about meteo basics in general.

3
00:00:22.530 --> 00:00:26.610
For me, there are two ways to approach learning meteorology.

4
00:00:26.750 --> 00:00:31.030
One is the minimum-effort approach — just getting through the theory exam somehow.

5
00:00:31.030 --> 00:00:36.840
And then of course there's a lot more weather knowledge you can teach and learn.

6
00:00:36.840 --> 00:00:42.430
There are basically no limits there — you could spend five days just talking about meteorology.

7
00:00:43.140 --> 00:00:46.800
But this course really focuses on the basics.

8
00:00:47.240 --> 00:00:50.540
It's also suitable for experienced pilots,

9
00:00:51.180 --> 00:00:56.220
to refresh their weather knowledge a bit or learn some new things.

10
00:00:56.400 --> 00:01:00.380
There are definitely some interesting topics in here for experienced pilots too.

11
00:01:00.680 --> 00:01:04.800
But this course is of course mainly designed for flight schools,

12
00:01:04.800 --> 00:01:08.810
so we can hopefully give you a good grasp of weather knowledge —

13
00:01:08.810 --> 00:01:14.150
stuff that might be rather dry in the theory book and a bit hard to understand.

14
00:01:14.150 --> 00:01:21.150
And so let's dive into the fascinating field of weather knowledge.

15
00:01:21.150 --> 00:01:26.480
One thing that's always very close to my heart, especially in meteorology,

16
00:01:26.480 --> 00:01:29.720
is that there are basically two sides to it.

17
00:01:29.720 --> 00:01:35.700
On one hand you have theoretical weather knowledge, where you can learn a lot and understand a lot of theory.

18
00:01:35.700 --> 00:01:38.700
But in meteorology, the weather happens out there in the open.

19
00:01:38.700 --> 00:01:43.700
It has a lot to do with experience — flight practice or hands-on meteo practice.

20
00:01:43.700 --> 00:01:48.700
A lot of it is about observing the weather over and over, analyzing it,

21
00:01:48.700 --> 00:01:51.700
and constantly matching theory with practice.

22
00:01:51.700 --> 00:01:53.700
And that's really important.

23
00:01:53.700 --> 00:02:00.720
But in this section, it's mainly about theory and building a basic understanding of the weather.

24
00:02:00.720 --> 00:02:05.760
Let's start with the biggest picture. Where does the weather actually happen?

25
00:02:05.760 --> 00:02:08.940
It happens in our atmosphere.

26
00:02:08.940 --> 00:02:14.270
The atmosphere around the world is divided into different layers.

27
00:02:14.270 --> 00:02:17.270
The stratosphere, mesosphere, troposphere.

28
00:02:17.270 --> 00:02:22.530
But the most relevant one for us is the troposphere,

29
00:02:22.530 --> 00:02:27.670
which is bounded at the top by what's called the tropopause.

30
00:02:27.670 --> 00:02:31.750
And this lower layer is where most of the humidity is found,

31
00:02:31.750 --> 00:02:37.310
most of the water vapour — and so it's what determines our weather.

32
00:02:37.310 --> 00:02:42.060
This troposphere is extremely thin.

33
00:02:42.060 --> 00:02:45.060
When you look from space, from a space station,

34
00:02:45.060 --> 00:02:49.060
it's just a very thin layer that you can see here.

35
00:02:49.060 --> 00:02:54.060
In scale, it's about as thin as an onion skin.

36
00:02:54.060 --> 00:02:59.060
It's really a very, very thin band where weather phenomena take place,

37
00:02:59.060 --> 00:03:01.060
and of course where we move around too.

38
00:03:01.060 --> 00:03:06.060
And we, as paraglider pilots, actually only move in the lowest layer of this troposphere.

39
00:03:06.060 --> 00:03:07.720
And...

40
00:03:07.720 --> 00:03:11.800
Something important from the theory — you also need to know this for the theory exam —

41
00:03:11.800 --> 00:03:16.070
the composition of the gases in this troposphere.

42
00:03:16.070 --> 00:03:22.410
There's the 21% oxygen, which is of course what we need to breathe,

43
00:03:22.410 --> 00:03:28.410
78% nitrogen, and then there's 1% noble gas,

44
00:03:28.410 --> 00:03:30.410
which is also part of the mix.

45
00:03:30.410 --> 00:03:34.410
But for us, for meteorology, that's not of much relevance —

46
00:03:34.410 --> 00:03:36.410
the remaining noble gases in there.

47
00:03:36.410 --> 00:03:45.550
The troposphere isn't equally thick all the way around the globe.

48
00:03:45.550 --> 00:03:50.790
It's a bit thinner at the poles than at the equator.

49
00:03:50.790 --> 00:03:52.790
That has to do with the Earth's rotation.

50
00:03:52.790 --> 00:04:00.900
At the equator it's about 18 km, and at the poles around 8 km.

51
00:04:00.900 --> 00:04:06.980
Here in Europe, at our latitude where we do most of our flying,

52
00:04:06.980 --> 00:04:11.980
the troposphere is about 11 to 13 km thick.

53
00:04:11.980 --> 00:04:18.020
You have to picture it — 13,000 metres.

54
00:04:18.020 --> 00:04:21.640
Then we talk about the standard atmosphere.

55
00:04:21.640 --> 00:04:26.660
This keeps coming up in flight weather, and especially in the theory exam.

56
00:04:26.660 --> 00:04:31.010
They'll keep asking you about the standard atmosphere.

57
00:04:31.010 --> 00:04:37.010
It's that atmosphere where the weather would be completely balanced out —

58
00:04:37.010 --> 00:04:39.010
no high-pressure areas, no low-pressure areas,

59
00:04:39.010 --> 00:04:42.010
and none of the various factors that influence our weather,

60
00:04:42.010 --> 00:04:44.010
which we'll look at in a moment.

61
00:04:44.010 --> 00:04:49.010
If everything balanced out, you'd get what's called the standard atmosphere.

62
00:04:49.010 --> 00:04:53.010
It's like the zero point, where everything has evened out.

63
00:04:53.010 --> 00:05:01.090
There are a few numbers and facts you need to know for the theory exam.

64
00:05:01.090 --> 00:05:05.970
The important one is the temperature gradient with altitude —

65
00:05:05.970 --> 00:05:09.970
how the troposphere cools off.

66
00:05:09.970 --> 00:05:13.970
We're talking about 6.5 degrees per 1000 metres,

67
00:05:13.970 --> 00:05:21.970
or per 100 metres, that's 0.65 degrees per 100 metres.

68
00:05:21.970 --> 00:05:28.370
At the Earth's surface, the standard atmosphere is 15 degrees,

69
00:05:28.370 --> 00:05:32.370
and at the top of the troposphere it's minus 56 degrees.

70
00:05:32.370 --> 00:05:34.740
The lower two numbers are especially important —

71
00:05:34.740 --> 00:05:38.740
make sure you learn those for the theory exam.

72
00:05:38.740 --> 00:05:43.730
The temperature gradient of course varies depending on the weather situation,

73
00:05:43.730 --> 00:05:47.730
as we'll see later.

74
00:05:47.730 --> 00:05:51.730
But in the standard atmosphere, as I said, it's 6.5 degrees per 100 metres.

75
00:05:51.730 --> 00:05:54.260
So those are the temperatures.

76
00:05:54.260 --> 00:05:58.260
In the standard atmosphere we also talk about a standard air pressure.

77
00:05:58.260 --> 00:06:02.590
We can't really get into air pressure yet,

78
00:06:02.590 --> 00:06:06.900
but the number we'll hear again and again

79
00:06:06.900 --> 00:06:08.900
is 1013.25 hPa.

80
00:06:08.900 --> 00:06:10.900
1013.25 hPa is the air pressure

81
00:06:10.900 --> 00:06:14.900
when the entire troposphere balances out, as I mentioned.

82
00:06:14.900 --> 00:06:20.900
Then, measured at sea level, the air pressure would always be the same.

83
00:06:20.900 --> 00:06:25.140
And it would be 1013.25 hPa.

84
00:06:25.140 --> 00:06:29.140
And the height of the troposphere, where the tropopause begins,

85
00:06:29.140 --> 00:06:34.270
is at 11 kilometres in the standard atmosphere.

86
00:06:34.270 --> 00:06:36.270
Another important thing about air pressure

87
00:06:36.270 --> 00:06:38.510
is how it drops with altitude.

88
00:06:38.510 --> 00:06:40.510
It's not linear.

89
00:06:40.510 --> 00:06:42.510
You can say

90
00:06:42.510 --> 00:06:46.510
that every 5500 metres of altitude, the air pressure halves.

91
00:06:46.510 --> 00:06:55.180
So at 5500 metres we'd have 506.6 hPa.

92
00:06:55.180 --> 00:06:57.180
That's also a value at 5500 metres

93
00:06:57.180 --> 00:07:01.180
that's very important to learn for the theory exam.

94
00:07:01.180 --> 00:07:05.390
So pressure of course decreases with altitude.

95
00:07:05.390 --> 00:07:07.390
You can picture air pressure like this:

96
00:07:07.390 --> 00:07:09.390
it's like a column of air

97
00:07:09.390 --> 00:07:11.390
that's above us all the way up to the tropopause.

98
00:07:11.390 --> 00:07:13.390
And it works the same way as in water, for example.

99
00:07:13.390 --> 00:07:15.390
For those who dive,

100
00:07:15.390 --> 00:07:17.390
the deeper you go into the water,

101
00:07:17.390 --> 00:07:21.390
the higher the pressure becomes due to Earth's gravity.

102
00:07:21.390 --> 00:07:25.570
And so naturally the air pressure is highest

103
00:07:25.570 --> 00:07:27.570
at the lowest point, at sea level,

104
00:07:27.570 --> 00:07:29.570
and decreases with altitude.

105
00:07:29.570 --> 00:07:31.570
It has to do with gravity

106
00:07:31.570 --> 00:07:33.940
and with the column of air

107
00:07:33.940 --> 00:07:35.940
that acts on us

108
00:07:35.940 --> 00:07:37.940
and generates air pressure.

109
00:07:37.940 --> 00:07:42.050
Here are the numbers quickly summarized again:

110
00:07:42.050 --> 00:07:44.050
1013.25, 15 degrees,

111
00:07:44.050 --> 00:07:46.050
and 0.65 per 100 metres.

112
00:07:46.050 --> 00:07:48.050
Those are the numbers

113
00:07:48.050 --> 00:07:50.050
that are relevant for us

114
00:07:50.050 --> 00:07:52.050
for the standard atmosphere.

115
00:07:52.050 --> 00:07:55.020
Right.

116
00:07:55.020 --> 00:07:57.200
And if we think about it,

117
00:07:57.200 --> 00:07:59.570
the standard atmosphere

118
00:07:59.570 --> 00:08:01.570
is of course never quite the same,

119
00:08:01.570 --> 00:08:03.570
as we experience every day with the weather.

120
00:08:03.570 --> 00:08:05.570
Enter the engine —

121
00:08:05.570 --> 00:08:07.570
the sun,

122
00:08:07.570 --> 00:08:09.580
which shines on the Earth and does its work.

123
00:08:09.580 --> 00:08:11.580
And different land and sea regions

124
00:08:11.580 --> 00:08:13.580
warm up differently.

125
00:08:13.580 --> 00:08:15.580
Different seasons too.

126
00:08:15.580 --> 00:08:17.580
With different angles of incidence

127
00:08:17.580 --> 00:08:19.580
of the sun depending on the season.

128
00:08:19.580 --> 00:08:21.580
You know how it is —

129
00:08:21.580 --> 00:08:23.580
the sun isn't always at the same height.

130
00:08:23.580 --> 00:08:25.580
And so the whole

131
00:08:25.580 --> 00:08:27.580
system, the standard atmosphere,

132
00:08:27.580 --> 00:08:29.580
gets thrown out of balance,

133
00:08:29.580 --> 00:08:31.580
and there are fluctuations in air pressure

134
00:08:31.580 --> 00:08:33.580
and all the various weather systems.

135
00:08:33.580 --> 00:08:35.580
So the sun is a really important engine

136
00:08:35.580 --> 00:08:37.580
that knocks things out of balance

137
00:08:37.580 --> 00:08:39.580
and influences the weather in various ways.

138
00:08:39.580 --> 00:08:41.580
And we're going to look at this together now —

139
00:08:41.580 --> 00:08:43.580
what kind of influence it has.

140
00:08:43.580 --> 00:08:46.080
The sun,

141
00:08:46.080 --> 00:08:49.780
shining on the Earth,

142
00:08:49.780 --> 00:08:52.020
primarily heats the ground.

143
00:08:52.020 --> 00:08:54.020
That's really important.

144
00:08:54.020 --> 00:08:56.020
The sun never heats an air mass

145
00:08:56.020 --> 00:08:58.020
that it passes through.

146
00:08:58.020 --> 00:09:00.020
Air doesn't reflect the sun

147
00:09:00.020 --> 00:09:02.020
or heat up from it.

148
00:09:02.020 --> 00:09:04.020
What it actually warms is

149
00:09:04.020 --> 00:09:06.020
the air layer near the ground.

150
00:09:06.020 --> 00:09:08.020
That's the air layer

151
00:09:08.020 --> 00:09:10.020
that sits right on the ground.

152
00:09:10.020 --> 00:09:12.020
Through the radiated heat

153
00:09:12.020 --> 00:09:14.020
that gets given off,

154
00:09:14.020 --> 00:09:16.420
the air layer near the ground heats up.

155
00:09:16.420 --> 00:09:18.420
And because of this warming

156
00:09:18.420 --> 00:09:20.420
of the air layer near the ground,

157
00:09:20.420 --> 00:09:22.420
there are regions across the world,

158
00:09:22.420 --> 00:09:24.420
spread across the globe,

159
00:09:24.420 --> 00:09:26.500
that warm up differently.

160
00:09:26.500 --> 00:09:28.500
Regions at the equator warm up

161
00:09:28.500 --> 00:09:30.500
much more than a region

162
00:09:30.500 --> 00:09:32.500
somewhere in the polar area,

163
00:09:32.500 --> 00:09:34.500
where the sun's rays

164
00:09:34.500 --> 00:09:36.500
only hit at a very shallow angle.

165
00:09:36.500 --> 00:09:38.500
Likewise, an ice surface

166
00:09:38.500 --> 00:09:40.500
warms up less

167
00:09:40.500 --> 00:09:42.500
than, say, a desert

168
00:09:42.500 --> 00:09:44.500
or a forested area, and so on.

169
00:09:44.500 --> 00:09:47.340
And because of that,

170
00:09:47.340 --> 00:09:49.340
different areas

171
00:09:49.340 --> 00:09:51.490
on the globe heat up differently,

172
00:09:51.490 --> 00:09:53.490
and this creates different

173
00:09:53.490 --> 00:09:55.490
air masses.

174
00:09:55.490 --> 00:09:57.730
When we talk about air masses —

175
00:09:57.730 --> 00:09:59.730
that's another word

176
00:09:59.730 --> 00:10:01.730
that comes up a lot in meteorology.

177
00:10:01.730 --> 00:10:03.780
An air mass is

178
00:10:03.780 --> 00:10:05.820
basically a volume of air

179
00:10:05.820 --> 00:10:07.820
that has the same properties.

180
00:10:07.820 --> 00:10:09.820
So we have, for instance, a warmer

181
00:10:09.820 --> 00:10:11.820
air mass and a cooler one.

182
00:10:11.820 --> 00:10:13.820
And these are always regions

183
00:10:13.820 --> 00:10:15.820
that have the same properties

184
00:10:15.820 --> 00:10:17.820
over several hundred kilometres —

185
00:10:17.820 --> 00:10:19.820
the same air pressure,

186
00:10:19.820 --> 00:10:21.820
or the same temperature,

187
00:10:21.820 --> 00:10:23.820
or similar temperature,

188
00:10:23.820 --> 00:10:27.900
a warmer or a colder temperature.

189
00:10:27.900 --> 00:10:29.900
Basically, the rule is:

190
00:10:29.900 --> 00:10:31.900
over an area that's been colder for longer

191
00:10:31.900 --> 00:10:33.920
than its surroundings,

192
00:10:33.920 --> 00:10:36.060
you'll get higher

193
00:10:36.060 --> 00:10:38.110
air pressure.

194
00:10:38.110 --> 00:10:40.110
And over an area that's been warm for longer

195
00:10:40.110 --> 00:10:42.290
than its surroundings,

196
00:10:42.290 --> 00:10:44.500
you get lower pressure.

197
00:10:44.500 --> 00:10:46.500
Accordingly, in the tropical

198
00:10:46.500 --> 00:10:48.500
regions, for example, you have the tropical

199
00:10:48.500 --> 00:10:50.700
low-pressure areas, and in the

200
00:10:50.700 --> 00:10:52.700
polar regions you have the polar

201
00:10:52.700 --> 00:10:54.820
high-pressure areas.

202
00:10:54.820 --> 00:10:56.820
That's how different air pressures arise.

203
00:10:56.820 --> 00:10:59.120
And then the low-pressure areas

204
00:10:59.120 --> 00:11:01.120
and high-pressure areas form,

205
00:11:01.120 --> 00:11:03.120
which we'll get into

206
00:11:03.120 --> 00:11:05.120
in the next slides,

207
00:11:05.120 --> 00:11:07.260
what kind of influence that

208
00:11:07.260 --> 00:11:09.980
has on our weather.

209
00:11:09.980 --> 00:11:11.980
You can imagine these

210
00:11:11.980 --> 00:11:13.980
as belts around the world.

211
00:11:13.980 --> 00:11:15.980
Around the globe there are what's called

212
00:11:15.980 --> 00:11:17.980
high-pressure cells.

213
00:11:17.980 --> 00:11:19.980
These are low- and high-pressure rings.

214
00:11:19.980 --> 00:11:22.450
There are even more than what's shown in this graphic.

215
00:11:22.450 --> 00:11:24.450
But basically, in

216
00:11:24.450 --> 00:11:26.450
the tropical regions you get a

217
00:11:26.450 --> 00:11:28.460
low-pressure belt, and in the polar regions you get

218
00:11:28.460 --> 00:11:30.740
a high-pressure belt.

219
00:11:30.740 --> 00:11:32.740
And so you also get tropical

220
00:11:32.740 --> 00:11:34.740
air masses and polar

221
00:11:34.740 --> 00:11:36.880
air masses. And here too, we'll

222
00:11:36.880 --> 00:11:39.120
learn over the next few minutes

223
00:11:39.120 --> 00:11:41.120
what kind of influence that has

224
00:11:41.120 --> 00:11:43.230
on our weather.

225
00:11:43.230 --> 00:11:46.210
We just covered this.

226
00:11:46.210 --> 00:11:48.220
Different regions

227
00:11:48.220 --> 00:11:50.220
warm up to different degrees.

228
00:11:50.220 --> 00:11:52.220
So you get a high-pressure area

229
00:11:52.220 --> 00:11:54.240
and a low-pressure area.

230
00:11:54.240 --> 00:11:56.240
And here in the middle you can see

231
00:11:56.240 --> 00:11:58.240
the numbers we just had

232
00:11:58.240 --> 00:12:00.240
from this standard atmosphere,

233
00:12:00.240 --> 00:12:02.240
the 1013.25.

234
00:12:02.240 --> 00:12:04.240
And as soon as the air pressure drops

235
00:12:04.240 --> 00:12:06.670
and is lower,

236
00:12:06.670 --> 00:12:08.670
we're talking about a low-pressure area.

237
00:12:08.670 --> 00:12:10.670
Here in Europe,

238
00:12:10.670 --> 00:12:12.670
a very pronounced

239
00:12:12.670 --> 00:12:14.670
low-pressure area is around

240
00:12:14.670 --> 00:12:16.670
955 hPa.

241
00:12:16.670 --> 00:12:18.670
And a very pronounced

242
00:12:18.670 --> 00:12:20.670
high-pressure area would be around

243
00:12:20.670 --> 00:12:22.690
1035 hPa.

244
00:12:22.690 --> 00:12:24.690
Now in this age of global warming,

245
00:12:24.690 --> 00:12:26.690
the values are unfortunately also getting

246
00:12:26.690 --> 00:12:28.690
more extreme. There are even

247
00:12:28.690 --> 00:12:30.690
high-pressure systems that reach, for example,

248
00:12:30.690 --> 00:12:32.690
1048 hPa.

249
00:12:32.690 --> 00:12:34.690
So those are

250
00:12:34.690 --> 00:12:36.690
very strong pressure differences.

251
00:12:36.690 --> 00:12:38.690
And accordingly,

252
00:12:38.690 --> 00:12:40.690
the meteorological phenomena are getting stronger too.

253
00:12:40.690 --> 00:12:42.690
And that's something we

254
00:12:42.690 --> 00:12:44.690
unfortunately keep experiencing.

255
00:12:44.690 --> 00:12:46.690
These severe weather events, for example,

256
00:12:46.690 --> 00:12:48.690
have a lot to do with

257
00:12:48.690 --> 00:12:50.690
these pressure swings that keep getting stronger.

258
00:12:50.690 --> 00:12:54.500
Something else that's important

259
00:12:54.500 --> 00:12:57.120
for us to know —

260
00:12:57.120 --> 00:12:59.120
we'll get back to the connection later —

261
00:12:59.120 --> 00:13:01.120
is that

262
00:13:01.120 --> 00:13:03.330
in high-pressure areas the air masses

263
00:13:03.330 --> 00:13:05.630
sink, and in low-pressure areas

264
00:13:05.630 --> 00:13:07.630
the air masses rise. That'll be

265
00:13:07.630 --> 00:13:09.630
really important later on

266
00:13:09.630 --> 00:13:11.630
for flight weather, which we'll

267
00:13:11.630 --> 00:13:13.630
get to in a bit.

268
00:13:13.630 --> 00:13:15.630
And basically, like every gas

269
00:13:15.630 --> 00:13:17.630
or every liquid,

270
00:13:17.630 --> 00:13:19.870
air masses have

271
00:13:19.870 --> 00:13:21.870
the urge to equalize pressure.

272
00:13:21.870 --> 00:13:23.950
That means

273
00:13:23.950 --> 00:13:25.950
an air mass always wants to flow from

274
00:13:25.950 --> 00:13:27.950
high pressure to low pressure,

275
00:13:27.950 --> 00:13:30.510
because it wants to equalize the pressure.

276
00:13:30.510 --> 00:13:32.510
And accordingly, especially

277
00:13:32.510 --> 00:13:34.510
at ground level or in the

278
00:13:34.510 --> 00:13:36.510
lower air layers, this

279
00:13:36.510 --> 00:13:38.560
airflow is important, that

280
00:13:38.560 --> 00:13:40.560
air flows from high to low,

281
00:13:40.560 --> 00:13:42.560
and that's how

282
00:13:42.560 --> 00:13:44.560
the winds form,

283
00:13:44.560 --> 00:13:46.560
the wind systems that we

284
00:13:46.560 --> 00:13:48.560
feel at ground level when the wind blows.

285
00:13:48.560 --> 00:13:50.770
And

286
00:13:50.770 --> 00:13:52.770
so there's an equalizing flow,

287
00:13:52.770 --> 00:13:54.770
which is important for us

288
00:13:54.770 --> 00:13:56.880
to identify these wind directions

289
00:13:56.880 --> 00:13:58.880
and read them out.

290
00:13:58.880 --> 00:14:02.860
Then we come to

291
00:14:02.860 --> 00:14:04.860
isobar charts — a word that

292
00:14:04.860 --> 00:14:06.860
you've surely heard before or read about

293
00:14:06.860 --> 00:14:08.860
in the theory book. There are

294
00:14:08.860 --> 00:14:10.860
weather charts that describe

295
00:14:10.860 --> 00:14:12.860
exactly these weather phenomena we just discussed.

296
00:14:12.860 --> 00:14:15.580
These weather charts

297
00:14:15.580 --> 00:14:17.580
come from a combination of

298
00:14:17.580 --> 00:14:19.580
current measurements,

299
00:14:19.580 --> 00:14:21.580
where barometers measure the

300
00:14:21.580 --> 00:14:23.580
air pressure, and

301
00:14:23.580 --> 00:14:25.580
of course the computer models,

302
00:14:25.580 --> 00:14:27.580
which then use those measurements

303
00:14:27.580 --> 00:14:29.580
to try and forecast

304
00:14:29.580 --> 00:14:31.580
and predict the weather.

305
00:14:31.580 --> 00:14:33.730
And then you end up with

306
00:14:33.730 --> 00:14:35.730
these fun weather charts,

307
00:14:35.730 --> 00:14:37.730
which we'll now look at in more detail

308
00:14:37.730 --> 00:14:39.730
and learn how to read.

309
00:14:39.730 --> 00:14:41.900
Isobar charts —

310
00:14:41.900 --> 00:14:43.920
isobars

311
00:14:43.920 --> 00:14:46.000
are the lines

312
00:14:46.000 --> 00:14:48.720
you see here. Isobars

313
00:14:48.720 --> 00:14:50.940
describe areas

314
00:14:50.940 --> 00:14:52.940
that have the same air pressure.

315
00:14:52.940 --> 00:14:54.940
Or where the same

316
00:14:54.940 --> 00:14:56.990
air pressure is forecast.

317
00:14:56.990 --> 00:14:58.990
So we have, for instance, an isobar

318
00:14:58.990 --> 00:15:00.990
at 1025 hPa —

319
00:15:00.990 --> 00:15:02.990
you can't see it well here, but in the next

320
00:15:02.990 --> 00:15:04.990
chart it's easier to see.

321
00:15:04.990 --> 00:15:06.990
And everywhere that line runs,

322
00:15:06.990 --> 00:15:08.990
at sea level — this is really important,

323
00:15:08.990 --> 00:15:10.990
the pressure is reduced to

324
00:15:10.990 --> 00:15:12.990
sea level — the same air pressure

325
00:15:12.990 --> 00:15:15.390
is present. That's where the name

326
00:15:15.390 --> 00:15:17.390
isobar charts comes from.

327
00:15:17.390 --> 00:15:19.390
Iso = equal, bar = pressure.

328
00:15:19.390 --> 00:15:21.390
So everywhere the same pressure

329
00:15:21.390 --> 00:15:23.410
occurs, this kind of line is

330
00:15:23.410 --> 00:15:26.290
drawn. And on such an

331
00:15:26.290 --> 00:15:28.290
isobar chart, fronts are often

332
00:15:28.290 --> 00:15:30.290
marked too, of course — we'll get into that

333
00:15:30.290 --> 00:15:32.290
in more detail later in this course,

334
00:15:32.290 --> 00:15:34.290
what these fronts look

335
00:15:34.290 --> 00:15:37.120
like.

336
00:15:37.120 --> 00:15:39.120
Here you can see slightly bigger isobar charts,

337
00:15:39.120 --> 00:15:41.120
showing again the high-pressure areas,

338
00:15:41.120 --> 00:15:43.120
low-pressure areas we just discussed,

339
00:15:43.120 --> 00:15:45.120
where different air pressure has

340
00:15:45.120 --> 00:15:47.120
developed, due to the sun and

341
00:15:47.120 --> 00:15:49.120
the seasons, for example.

342
00:15:49.120 --> 00:15:51.890
And that's

343
00:15:51.890 --> 00:15:53.890
what a somewhat larger

344
00:15:53.890 --> 00:15:55.890
isobar chart looks like. They always look a bit

345
00:15:55.890 --> 00:15:57.890
different, depending on the newspaper

346
00:15:57.890 --> 00:15:59.890
or meteo service.

347
00:15:59.890 --> 00:16:01.890
They look a bit different, but in principle

348
00:16:01.890 --> 00:16:03.890
they all have the same elements

349
00:16:03.890 --> 00:16:05.890
in them. There are again the high and

350
00:16:05.890 --> 00:16:07.890
low-pressure areas, isobars, and

351
00:16:07.890 --> 00:16:09.890
the colored lines, the

352
00:16:09.890 --> 00:16:15.630
fronts. Right.

353
00:16:15.630 --> 00:16:17.630
That's what it also looks like. Now once again,

354
00:16:17.630 --> 00:16:19.740
shown simply on our

355
00:16:19.740 --> 00:16:21.740
globe, the different pressure areas

356
00:16:21.740 --> 00:16:23.740
that form over various land and

357
00:16:23.740 --> 00:16:25.760
sea masses.

358
00:16:25.760 --> 00:16:27.760
They have different pressure — again

359
00:16:27.760 --> 00:16:29.780
low-pressure — and

360
00:16:29.780 --> 00:16:32.370
due to the Coriolis force,

361
00:16:32.370 --> 00:16:34.670
which is a

362
00:16:34.670 --> 00:16:36.670
physical phenomenon caused by

363
00:16:36.670 --> 00:16:38.780
the Earth's rotation,

364
00:16:38.780 --> 00:16:40.800
different

365
00:16:40.800 --> 00:16:42.800
air masses,

366
00:16:42.800 --> 00:16:44.800
as they start to move,

367
00:16:44.800 --> 00:16:47.010
get deflected.

368
00:16:47.010 --> 00:16:49.010
And that produces

369
00:16:49.010 --> 00:16:51.010
cyclical movements —

370
00:16:51.010 --> 00:16:53.010
rotating movements.

371
00:16:53.010 --> 00:16:55.010
Picture it like

372
00:16:55.010 --> 00:16:57.010
a drain for instance —

373
00:16:57.010 --> 00:16:59.010
due to various forces

374
00:16:59.010 --> 00:17:01.010
or the shape of the drain you get

375
00:17:01.010 --> 00:17:03.010
a whirlpool. When

376
00:17:03.010 --> 00:17:05.010
the water flows down the drain,

377
00:17:05.010 --> 00:17:07.010
it starts to rotate.

378
00:17:07.010 --> 00:17:09.010
And so a rotational motion arises.

379
00:17:09.010 --> 00:17:11.010
In the air mass it's

380
00:17:11.010 --> 00:17:13.010
mainly the Coriolis force that's responsible

381
00:17:13.010 --> 00:17:15.010
for the

382
00:17:15.010 --> 00:17:17.280
air masses starting to

383
00:17:17.280 --> 00:17:19.940
rotate. And consequently,

384
00:17:19.940 --> 00:17:21.940
on the northern side

385
00:17:21.940 --> 00:17:24.140
of our globe,

386
00:17:24.140 --> 00:17:26.140
everything north of

387
00:17:26.140 --> 00:17:28.140
the equator, it's the case

388
00:17:28.140 --> 00:17:30.140
that in a high-pressure area

389
00:17:30.140 --> 00:17:32.480
the air masses rotate

390
00:17:32.480 --> 00:17:34.480
clockwise, and

391
00:17:34.480 --> 00:17:36.480
in a low-pressure area

392
00:17:36.480 --> 00:17:38.480
counterclockwise.

393
00:17:38.480 --> 00:17:40.480
I came up with a memory trick:

394
00:17:40.480 --> 00:17:42.480
a high-pressure area is something positive for me,

395
00:17:42.480 --> 00:17:44.480
because then the sun shines and the

396
00:17:44.480 --> 00:17:46.480
weather is nice and it's flying weather.

397
00:17:46.480 --> 00:17:48.480
So it's something positive.

398
00:17:48.480 --> 00:17:50.480
And to me, clockwise is

399
00:17:50.480 --> 00:17:52.480
time running forward — in a positive sense.

400
00:17:52.480 --> 00:17:54.480
Moving forward, I built that as a memory aid:

401
00:17:54.480 --> 00:17:56.480
in a high-pressure area

402
00:17:56.480 --> 00:17:58.480
clockwise, in a low-pressure area

403
00:17:58.480 --> 00:18:00.500
counterclockwise — the rotation.

404
00:18:00.500 --> 00:18:02.900
In the southern

405
00:18:02.900 --> 00:18:04.900
hemisphere, for example

406
00:18:04.900 --> 00:18:06.900
in Australia, the whole thing

407
00:18:06.900 --> 00:18:08.900
works exactly the opposite.

408
00:18:08.900 --> 00:18:10.900
Just for those of you who fly off on holiday

409
00:18:10.900 --> 00:18:12.900
and go flying in South America,

410
00:18:12.900 --> 00:18:14.900
or in Australia,

411
00:18:14.900 --> 00:18:18.670
there it's exactly reversed.

412
00:18:18.670 --> 00:18:20.670
You can see this very impressively

413
00:18:20.670 --> 00:18:22.670
of course in the case of

414
00:18:22.670 --> 00:18:24.750
a hurricane. You can really see

415
00:18:24.750 --> 00:18:26.750
how the air mass rotates. A

416
00:18:26.750 --> 00:18:28.750
hurricane is nothing other than

417
00:18:28.750 --> 00:18:30.750
an extreme low-pressure area,

418
00:18:30.750 --> 00:18:32.830
and you can see —

419
00:18:32.830 --> 00:18:34.830
this is a hurricane,

420
00:18:34.830 --> 00:18:36.910
it's in the northern

421
00:18:36.910 --> 00:18:38.910
hemisphere — you can see how it

422
00:18:38.910 --> 00:18:40.910
rotates counterclockwise

423
00:18:40.910 --> 00:18:42.960
and gets sucked into the low-pressure

424
00:18:42.960 --> 00:18:44.980
area, this air mass.

425
00:18:44.980 --> 00:18:47.120
You can see it

426
00:18:47.120 --> 00:18:49.120
very nicely in this

427
00:18:49.120 --> 00:18:52.610
cloud image of a hurricane.

428
00:18:52.610 --> 00:18:55.010
And accordingly — we saw earlier

429
00:18:55.010 --> 00:18:57.010
in the slide that the air mass

430
00:18:57.010 --> 00:18:59.010
wants to equalize the pressure, it flows

431
00:18:59.010 --> 00:19:01.010
from high pressure into the low-pressure area,

432
00:19:01.010 --> 00:19:03.010
but it doesn't flow in a direct

433
00:19:03.010 --> 00:19:05.010
line from

434
00:19:05.010 --> 00:19:07.010
high to low, instead it gets

435
00:19:07.010 --> 00:19:09.010
deflected, as the Coriolis force describes,

436
00:19:09.010 --> 00:19:11.010
into a rotating motion

437
00:19:11.010 --> 00:19:13.010
as it moves between the areas.

438
00:19:13.010 --> 00:19:15.010
So the

439
00:19:15.010 --> 00:19:17.010
air mass goes in this

440
00:19:17.010 --> 00:19:19.010
spiral motion

441
00:19:19.010 --> 00:19:21.600
right into the low-pressure area.

442
00:19:21.600 --> 00:19:28.400
To read out the wind direction,

443
00:19:28.400 --> 00:19:30.400
we'll look at that

444
00:19:30.400 --> 00:19:32.400
on the chart in a moment —

445
00:19:32.400 --> 00:19:34.400
we'll see again in a few

446
00:19:34.400 --> 00:19:36.400
slides later how you read

447
00:19:36.400 --> 00:19:38.400
the wind direction off an isobar chart.

448
00:19:38.400 --> 00:19:41.230
You can also read

449
00:19:41.230 --> 00:19:43.230
wind strength

450
00:19:43.230 --> 00:19:45.230
from this isobar chart.

451
00:19:45.230 --> 00:19:47.230
Maybe to describe it visually,

452
00:19:47.230 --> 00:19:49.230
you can think of an isobar chart

453
00:19:49.230 --> 00:19:51.230
a bit like a

454
00:19:51.230 --> 00:19:53.230
topographic map.

455
00:19:53.230 --> 00:19:55.230
Those are different contour lines —

456
00:19:55.230 --> 00:19:57.440
different pressure lines — and accordingly

457
00:19:57.440 --> 00:19:59.440
a high-pressure area, for example, can

458
00:19:59.440 --> 00:20:01.550
be of different heights.

459
00:20:01.550 --> 00:20:03.550
So a high-pressure influence can

460
00:20:03.550 --> 00:20:05.660
be of varying strength.

461
00:20:05.660 --> 00:20:07.660
We might have, for instance,

462
00:20:07.660 --> 00:20:09.660
a 50er of a high-pressure area —

463
00:20:09.660 --> 00:20:11.660
extremely strong, it has lots of

464
00:20:11.660 --> 00:20:13.660
isobar lines, lots of contour lines

465
00:20:13.660 --> 00:20:15.660
in the landscape sense.

466
00:20:15.660 --> 00:20:17.660
Or it could just be a hill,

467
00:20:17.660 --> 00:20:19.970
but the H

468
00:20:19.970 --> 00:20:21.980
really only describes the

469
00:20:21.980 --> 00:20:23.980
highest pressure point — basically

470
00:20:23.980 --> 00:20:25.980
the highest elevation in the landscape

471
00:20:25.980 --> 00:20:27.980
or of that hill.

472
00:20:27.980 --> 00:20:29.980
And so it can be higher

473
00:20:29.980 --> 00:20:32.670
or less high. And accordingly

474
00:20:32.670 --> 00:20:34.670
the weather effects,

475
00:20:34.670 --> 00:20:36.670
which we'll discuss in a moment,

476
00:20:36.670 --> 00:20:40.860
are stronger or weaker.

477
00:20:40.860 --> 00:20:42.860
What we're going to do is quickly look at

478
00:20:42.860 --> 00:20:44.860
how to read a wind direction

479
00:20:44.860 --> 00:20:47.330
off such an isobar chart.

480
00:20:47.330 --> 00:20:49.330
Basically we have —

481
00:20:49.330 --> 00:20:51.330
this is an infographic from a

482
00:20:51.330 --> 00:20:53.660
theory exam, like the one you'll get —

483
00:20:53.660 --> 00:20:55.660
we have different pressure areas,

484
00:20:55.660 --> 00:20:57.780
like the ones we've seen.

485
00:20:57.780 --> 00:20:59.780
Of course they won't make your exam

486
00:20:59.780 --> 00:21:01.780
so easy that they put an H and a T

487
00:21:01.780 --> 00:21:03.780
in there for you so you immediately know where the

488
00:21:03.780 --> 00:21:05.780
high and low-pressure areas are. So

489
00:21:05.780 --> 00:21:07.780
they want you to read the pressure

490
00:21:07.780 --> 00:21:09.780
off these isobars, and

491
00:21:09.780 --> 00:21:11.780
you see for example here over Scandinavia,

492
00:21:11.780 --> 00:21:13.780
it's relatively hard to read,

493
00:21:13.780 --> 00:21:15.780
80 hPa for instance.

494
00:21:15.780 --> 00:21:17.780
You know that's below

495
00:21:17.780 --> 00:21:19.780
1013.25.

496
00:21:19.780 --> 00:21:21.780
So that has to be a low pressure.

497
00:21:21.780 --> 00:21:23.780
So there you can imagine,

498
00:21:23.780 --> 00:21:25.780
you can even write a T in there

499
00:21:25.780 --> 00:21:27.780
if you want.

500
00:21:27.780 --> 00:21:29.780
And so we know that the

501
00:21:29.780 --> 00:21:31.780
air mass in this low-pressure area

502
00:21:31.780 --> 00:21:33.790
rotates counterclockwise.

503
00:21:33.790 --> 00:21:36.380
And then you can,

504
00:21:36.380 --> 00:21:38.380
if you want, draw arrows

505
00:21:38.380 --> 00:21:40.380
onto these isobar lines you see here,

506
00:21:40.380 --> 00:21:42.380
or you can also just

507
00:21:42.380 --> 00:21:44.380
picture it —

508
00:21:44.380 --> 00:21:46.380
imagine arrows on the

509
00:21:46.380 --> 00:21:48.380
isobar lines.

510
00:21:48.380 --> 00:21:50.940
I've shown them in white here,

511
00:21:50.940 --> 00:21:52.940
and that's how you read the wind direction.

512
00:21:52.940 --> 00:21:55.060
So for example here

513
00:21:55.060 --> 00:21:57.060
in England we have

514
00:21:57.060 --> 00:21:59.490
a westerly wind flow.

515
00:21:59.490 --> 00:22:01.490
And in the high-pressure area,

516
00:22:01.490 --> 00:22:03.490
here we have 1030 hPa,

517
00:22:03.490 --> 00:22:05.490
that's where the highest elevation is,

518
00:22:05.490 --> 00:22:07.490
that's where the high pressure is, that's where it rotates

519
00:22:07.490 --> 00:22:09.490
clockwise, and so

520
00:22:09.490 --> 00:22:11.490
the wind follows the isobars.

521
00:22:11.490 --> 00:22:13.490
And you can really

522
00:22:13.490 --> 00:22:15.490
see, for the theory it's the case

523
00:22:15.490 --> 00:22:17.490
that the wind is always read

524
00:22:17.490 --> 00:22:19.490
parallel to the isobars.

525
00:22:19.490 --> 00:22:21.660
So you really take the line,

526
00:22:21.660 --> 00:22:24.190
and that's the wind direction,

527
00:22:24.190 --> 00:22:26.190
because the pressure equalizes

528
00:22:26.190 --> 00:22:30.210
in a circulating motion.

529
00:22:30.210 --> 00:22:32.820
Right, that's for the wind direction.

530
00:22:32.820 --> 00:22:34.820
You can also picture

531
00:22:34.820 --> 00:22:36.820
high- and low-pressure areas

532
00:22:36.820 --> 00:22:38.820
as working like a gear system.

533
00:22:38.820 --> 00:22:40.820
You can imagine

534
00:22:40.820 --> 00:22:42.820
them as two gears

535
00:22:42.820 --> 00:22:44.820
that mesh into each other —

536
00:22:44.820 --> 00:22:46.820
you might find that easier to picture.

537
00:22:46.820 --> 00:22:49.260
How to read the wind,

538
00:22:49.260 --> 00:22:51.260
we'll now look at

539
00:22:51.260 --> 00:22:53.500
in the next slides.

540
00:22:53.500 --> 00:22:55.810
One thing that's relevant for the wind

541
00:22:55.810 --> 00:22:57.810
is the wind direction.

542
00:22:57.810 --> 00:22:59.810
We need to know what wind direction to expect,

543
00:22:59.810 --> 00:23:01.810
which launch site to go to,

544
00:23:01.810 --> 00:23:03.810
where it's perhaps more relevant,

545
00:23:03.810 --> 00:23:05.860
also for various weather phenomena.

546
00:23:05.860 --> 00:23:07.860
You can picture

547
00:23:07.860 --> 00:23:09.870
a compass rose with north 0 degrees,

548
00:23:09.870 --> 00:23:11.870
east 90 degrees, south 180 degrees,

549
00:23:11.870 --> 00:23:13.870
west 270 degrees.

550
00:23:13.870 --> 00:23:15.870
And so the wind

551
00:23:15.870 --> 00:23:17.870
is sometimes given in degrees,

552
00:23:17.870 --> 00:23:19.870
out of these 360 degrees.

553
00:23:19.870 --> 00:23:22.780
A wind direction is always described

554
00:23:22.780 --> 00:23:24.780
by where the wind comes from.

555
00:23:24.780 --> 00:23:26.780
If the wind comes from the south,

556
00:23:26.780 --> 00:23:28.830
we call it a south wind —

557
00:23:28.830 --> 00:23:30.830
north wind, west wind, of course.

558
00:23:30.830 --> 00:23:32.830
So the air mass comes from the west

559
00:23:32.830 --> 00:23:34.830
and that makes it a west wind.

560
00:23:34.830 --> 00:23:37.010
And so the degrees

561
00:23:37.010 --> 00:23:39.010
are given accordingly.

562
00:23:39.010 --> 00:23:41.010
If we have a wind from 90 degrees,

563
00:23:41.010 --> 00:23:43.010
then picture the compass rose

564
00:23:43.010 --> 00:23:45.120
and the wind comes

565
00:23:45.120 --> 00:23:47.120
from 90 degrees, from the east.

566
00:23:47.120 --> 00:23:49.260
That's really important,

567
00:23:49.260 --> 00:23:51.260
because on the meteo theory exam

568
00:23:51.260 --> 00:23:53.260
the wind will keep being given

569
00:23:53.260 --> 00:23:55.260
in degrees.

570
00:23:55.260 --> 00:23:57.260
And then you need to know

571
00:23:57.260 --> 00:23:59.380
what they're talking about —

572
00:23:59.380 --> 00:24:01.620
are they talking about a south wind or an east wind, and so on.

573
00:24:01.620 --> 00:24:05.060
Then there's also wind strength.

574
00:24:05.060 --> 00:24:07.060
We just covered wind direction.

575
00:24:07.060 --> 00:24:09.060
Wind strength comes in

576
00:24:09.060 --> 00:24:11.200
various units.

577
00:24:11.200 --> 00:24:13.200
In aviation,

578
00:24:13.200 --> 00:24:15.200
and this comes mostly from aviation,

579
00:24:15.200 --> 00:24:17.200
the wind is usually

580
00:24:17.200 --> 00:24:19.200
given in knots.

581
00:24:19.200 --> 00:24:21.200
There's a simple formula.

582
00:24:21.200 --> 00:24:23.200
Wind in knots —

583
00:24:23.200 --> 00:24:25.250
so in the upper example

584
00:24:25.250 --> 00:24:27.250
nautical knots,

585
00:24:27.250 --> 00:24:29.360
times 2 minus 10%

586
00:24:29.360 --> 00:24:31.360
gives you km/h.

587
00:24:31.360 --> 00:24:33.360
So kilometres per hour of wind.

588
00:24:33.360 --> 00:24:35.360
Which for us is a bit

589
00:24:35.360 --> 00:24:37.360
the standard unit

590
00:24:37.360 --> 00:24:39.360
for wind speeds,

591
00:24:39.360 --> 00:24:41.360
we can picture it better.

592
00:24:41.360 --> 00:24:43.820
And at most weather stations

593
00:24:43.820 --> 00:24:45.820
for instance, the wind is given in km/h.

594
00:24:45.820 --> 00:24:47.820
Times 2 gives 40, minus 10%,

595
00:24:47.820 --> 00:24:49.820
that's 4,

596
00:24:49.820 --> 00:24:51.820
gives 36 km/h of wind.

597
00:24:51.820 --> 00:24:54.320
The conversion is important,

598
00:24:54.320 --> 00:24:56.320
make sure you have it on the tip of your tongue

599
00:24:56.320 --> 00:24:59.680
and ready for the theory exam.

600
00:24:59.680 --> 00:25:01.680
Then, something else you can include

601
00:25:01.680 --> 00:25:03.680
in the wind topic

602
00:25:03.680 --> 00:25:06.110
is the wind gradient.

603
00:25:06.110 --> 00:25:08.110
If you imagine

604
00:25:08.110 --> 00:25:10.110
a wind system coming in here,

605
00:25:10.110 --> 00:25:12.110
with a westerly wind,

606
00:25:12.110 --> 00:25:14.110
and it glides over the Earth's surface,

607
00:25:14.110 --> 00:25:16.110
the wind aloft

608
00:25:16.110 --> 00:25:18.480
is usually stronger,

609
00:25:18.480 --> 00:25:20.480
while down at the ground the wind has friction,

610
00:25:20.480 --> 00:25:22.480
so it becomes slower,

611
00:25:22.480 --> 00:25:24.480
but also somewhat more turbulent.

612
00:25:24.480 --> 00:25:26.480
So there are

613
00:25:26.480 --> 00:25:28.480
some basic rules:

614
00:25:28.480 --> 00:25:30.480
in low layers,

615
00:25:30.480 --> 00:25:32.480
in ground-level layers,

616
00:25:32.480 --> 00:25:34.480
the wind is weaker but more turbulent,

617
00:25:34.480 --> 00:25:36.480
and in higher air layers

618
00:25:36.480 --> 00:25:38.750
it's stronger but more laminar.

619
00:25:38.750 --> 00:25:40.750
Logically, then, there are also

620
00:25:40.750 --> 00:25:42.750
various meteorological phenomena,

621
00:25:42.750 --> 00:25:44.750
where perhaps occasionally

622
00:25:44.750 --> 00:25:46.750
a more turbulent air mass

623
00:25:46.750 --> 00:25:48.750
can be aloft, or the whole thing,

624
00:25:48.750 --> 00:25:50.750
and a basic rule is:

625
00:25:50.750 --> 00:25:52.750
if you know a wind flow,

626
00:25:52.750 --> 00:25:54.900
it's weaker and more turbulent at the ground.

627
00:25:54.900 --> 00:25:56.900
So that's the wind gradient.

628
00:25:56.900 --> 00:25:58.940
A gradient, by the way, is always

629
00:25:58.940 --> 00:26:00.940
a progression — in this sense,

630
00:26:00.940 --> 00:26:02.940
with altitude.

631
00:26:02.940 --> 00:26:04.940
We'll also hear about a temperature gradient

632
00:26:04.940 --> 00:26:06.940
later in the theory course.

633
00:26:06.940 --> 00:26:08.940
It always refers to a progression

634
00:26:08.940 --> 00:26:10.940
with altitude when you talk about a gradient,

635
00:26:10.940 --> 00:26:12.940
or in general a progression.

636
00:26:12.940 --> 00:26:14.940
But in meteorology it's

637
00:26:14.940 --> 00:26:17.150
mainly about altitude.

638
00:26:17.150 --> 00:26:20.450
Another topic that belongs to wind,

639
00:26:20.450 --> 00:26:22.450
that's especially important for us paraglider pilots,

640
00:26:22.450 --> 00:26:24.450
is turbulence.

641
00:26:24.450 --> 00:26:26.450
We want a calm flight if possible,

642
00:26:26.450 --> 00:26:28.450
or rather, when there is turbulence,

643
00:26:28.450 --> 00:26:30.450
we want to be prepared and know

644
00:26:30.450 --> 00:26:32.450
why this turbulence forms

645
00:26:32.450 --> 00:26:34.450
and how we can perhaps

646
00:26:34.450 --> 00:26:36.450
anticipate it a little,

647
00:26:36.450 --> 00:26:38.450
and in which areas we should fly,

648
00:26:38.450 --> 00:26:40.450
or maybe not.

649
00:26:40.450 --> 00:26:42.450
There are basically three types

650
00:26:42.450 --> 00:26:44.450
of turbulence that we distinguish,

651
00:26:44.450 --> 00:26:46.560
which also come up on the theory exam.

652
00:26:46.560 --> 00:26:48.560
First of all, certainly the best turbulence —

653
00:26:48.560 --> 00:26:50.560
which can be pleasant,

654
00:26:50.560 --> 00:26:52.560
but maybe also less pleasant —

655
00:26:52.560 --> 00:26:54.560
is thermal turbulence.

656
00:26:54.560 --> 00:26:56.560
That's probably the one we're

657
00:26:56.560 --> 00:26:58.560
exposed to the most when flying,

658
00:26:58.560 --> 00:27:00.560
because we want to fly thermally,

659
00:27:00.560 --> 00:27:02.560
so we're always moving

660
00:27:02.560 --> 00:27:04.560
in thermal air masses.

661
00:27:04.560 --> 00:27:06.560
And those who have felt it before

662
00:27:06.560 --> 00:27:08.930
know what I'm talking about.

663
00:27:08.930 --> 00:27:10.930
It's like this: when an air mass rises,

664
00:27:10.930 --> 00:27:12.930
the air mass is basically relatively calm —

665
00:27:12.930 --> 00:27:14.930
it sits here, and then the thermal

666
00:27:14.930 --> 00:27:16.930
turbulences rise, which we'll look at

667
00:27:16.930 --> 00:27:18.930
later in detail.

668
00:27:18.930 --> 00:27:20.930
And in this rising zone there are

669
00:27:20.930 --> 00:27:22.930
often small downdraft zones around the edges

670
00:27:22.930 --> 00:27:24.930
of thermal updrafts.

671
00:27:24.930 --> 00:27:26.930
And so you get wind shears

672
00:27:26.930 --> 00:27:28.930
in the vertical.

673
00:27:28.930 --> 00:27:30.930
And in these wind shears

674
00:27:30.930 --> 00:27:32.930
you of course feel the turbulence —

675
00:27:32.930 --> 00:27:35.300
that's the thermal turbulence.

676
00:27:35.300 --> 00:27:37.300
Then there's wind shear in another sense.

677
00:27:37.300 --> 00:27:39.300
That's when

678
00:27:39.300 --> 00:27:41.920
we have two different wind directions —

679
00:27:41.920 --> 00:27:43.920
if down low we have west wind

680
00:27:43.920 --> 00:27:45.920
and up top we have, or no,

681
00:27:45.920 --> 00:27:47.920
down low we might still have a bit of

682
00:27:47.920 --> 00:27:49.920
Bise mixed in, so east wind,

683
00:27:49.920 --> 00:27:51.920
up top we have west wind.

684
00:27:51.920 --> 00:27:53.920
Then there's sometimes a mixing layer

685
00:27:53.920 --> 00:27:55.920
where the two wind systems meet.

686
00:27:55.920 --> 00:27:57.920
And exactly at

687
00:27:57.920 --> 00:27:59.920
those altitudes where the winds

688
00:27:59.920 --> 00:28:01.920
meet, you get what's called a shear wind.

689
00:28:01.920 --> 00:28:04.060
And there too we

690
00:28:04.060 --> 00:28:06.060
perceive turbulence, or a light

691
00:28:06.060 --> 00:28:09.230
turbulence, depending on wind strength.

692
00:28:09.230 --> 00:28:11.230
For us paraglider pilots

693
00:28:11.230 --> 00:28:13.230
this isn't especially relevant.

694
00:28:13.230 --> 00:28:15.230
But sometimes we feel things,

695
00:28:15.230 --> 00:28:17.230
that there's a layer that rumbles a bit.

696
00:28:17.230 --> 00:28:19.440
For instance, due to a real wind.

697
00:28:19.440 --> 00:28:22.220
We'll come back to that later.

698
00:28:22.220 --> 00:28:25.300
With mechanical turbulence,

699
00:28:25.300 --> 00:28:27.300
that's the third topic,

700
00:28:27.300 --> 00:28:29.300
it's about when an

701
00:28:29.300 --> 00:28:31.300
air mass flows over an object,

702
00:28:31.300 --> 00:28:33.300
for instance a forest, or a house,

703
00:28:33.300 --> 00:28:35.300
or something — or even,

704
00:28:35.300 --> 00:28:37.300
and this is what's most relevant for us,

705
00:28:37.300 --> 00:28:39.300
a mountain range for instance —

706
00:28:39.300 --> 00:28:41.500
when we have strong wind there,

707
00:28:41.500 --> 00:28:43.500
and it flows over this object,

708
00:28:43.500 --> 00:28:45.500
you might know it from those

709
00:28:45.500 --> 00:28:47.500
airflow videos of cars and such,

710
00:28:47.500 --> 00:28:49.500
and then behind the object you get

711
00:28:49.500 --> 00:28:51.550
turbulent eddies,

712
00:28:51.550 --> 00:28:53.550
which can be very unpleasant.

713
00:28:53.550 --> 00:28:55.550
Depending on wind strength

714
00:28:55.550 --> 00:28:57.550
they can be very unpleasant,

715
00:28:57.550 --> 00:28:59.550
or even dangerous.

716
00:28:59.550 --> 00:29:01.550
But when the wind is rather weak,

717
00:29:01.550 --> 00:29:03.550
they're sometimes just subtly noticeable.

718
00:29:03.550 --> 00:29:05.550
Especially at the landing site this is important,

719
00:29:05.550 --> 00:29:07.550
if you'd be landing behind a house.

720
00:29:07.550 --> 00:29:09.550
If you have strong wind,

721
00:29:09.550 --> 00:29:11.550
that's of course not really an advantage.

722
00:29:11.550 --> 00:29:14.030
Maybe two more words here

723
00:29:14.030 --> 00:29:16.030
that come up again and again in flying:

724
00:29:16.030 --> 00:29:18.030
windward and lee.

725
00:29:18.030 --> 00:29:20.500
That's a topic we'll also

726
00:29:20.500 --> 00:29:22.500
look at briefly.

727
00:29:22.500 --> 00:29:24.500
The lee side always describes

728
00:29:24.500 --> 00:29:26.500
the side facing away from the wind,

729
00:29:26.500 --> 00:29:28.500
and the windward side is the side facing into the wind.

730
00:29:28.500 --> 00:29:30.800
The question always is,

731
00:29:30.800 --> 00:29:32.800
from whose perspective?

732
00:29:32.800 --> 00:29:34.800
From our perspective?

733
00:29:34.800 --> 00:29:36.800
From an object's perspective?

734
00:29:36.800 --> 00:29:38.800
Or — you hear it,

735
00:29:38.800 --> 00:29:40.800
you hear a lot of talk at the launch site,

736
00:29:40.800 --> 00:29:42.800
for instance also on mountain ridges.

737
00:29:42.800 --> 00:29:44.800
Down there we have a lee side,

738
00:29:44.800 --> 00:29:46.800
and that's seen from the mountain's perspective —

739
00:29:46.800 --> 00:29:48.800
the back side of the mountain,

740
00:29:48.800 --> 00:29:50.800
when the airflow hits the mountain.

741
00:29:50.800 --> 00:29:53.040
Or in this sense maybe

742
00:29:53.040 --> 00:29:55.040
a house — a lee side of the house

743
00:29:55.040 --> 00:29:57.040
and a windward side of the house.

744
00:29:57.040 --> 00:29:59.040
When landing you want exactly the same.

745
00:29:59.040 --> 00:30:01.040
We land on the windward side,

746
00:30:01.040 --> 00:30:03.040
as seen from the landing site,

747
00:30:03.040 --> 00:30:05.040
on the windward side,

748
00:30:05.040 --> 00:30:07.180
the side facing into the wind.

749
00:30:07.180 --> 00:30:09.180
So that's windward and lee.

750
00:30:09.180 --> 00:30:11.180
Something you'll hear over and over

751
00:30:11.180 --> 00:30:13.180
in your training and in meteo theory.

752
00:30:13.180 --> 00:30:16.430
Then we come to the last

753
00:30:16.430 --> 00:30:19.010
weather phenomenon

754
00:30:19.010 --> 00:30:21.010
involving wind,

755
00:30:21.010 --> 00:30:23.570
which is also really really important for us

756
00:30:23.570 --> 00:30:25.570
as paraglider pilots.

757
00:30:25.570 --> 00:30:27.570
And that's understanding

758
00:30:27.570 --> 00:30:29.570
the Venturi effect.

759
00:30:29.570 --> 00:30:31.570
The so-called Venturi effect

760
00:30:31.570 --> 00:30:33.570
you might know from aerodynamics theory.

761
00:30:33.570 --> 00:30:35.580
You'll go through it there in more detail.

762
00:30:35.580 --> 00:30:37.760
The Venturi effect

763
00:30:37.760 --> 00:30:39.760
is about this:

764
00:30:39.760 --> 00:30:41.760
whenever a wind flow

765
00:30:41.760 --> 00:30:43.760
or an air mass

766
00:30:43.760 --> 00:30:45.760
is forced

767
00:30:45.760 --> 00:30:47.760
to narrow,

768
00:30:47.760 --> 00:30:49.760
in the first example

769
00:30:49.760 --> 00:30:51.760
for instance a valley — if we have a wide valley

770
00:30:51.760 --> 00:30:53.870
that narrows to a smaller one

771
00:30:53.870 --> 00:30:55.870
and the wind gets pushed through there,

772
00:30:55.870 --> 00:30:57.870
a valley wind for example,

773
00:30:57.870 --> 00:30:59.950
then in the narrowing of the valley

774
00:30:59.950 --> 00:31:01.950
you get a wind acceleration.

775
00:31:01.950 --> 00:31:03.950
So there you have significantly stronger wind

776
00:31:03.950 --> 00:31:05.950
than on the wide side of the valley.

777
00:31:05.950 --> 00:31:07.970
So of course, if you're flying

778
00:31:07.970 --> 00:31:09.970
and expect a lot of wind,

779
00:31:09.970 --> 00:31:11.970
land in an open valley

780
00:31:11.970 --> 00:31:13.970
rather than in a narrow gorge,

781
00:31:13.970 --> 00:31:16.240
for example.

782
00:31:16.240 --> 00:31:19.250
That's the Venturi effect.

783
00:31:19.250 --> 00:31:21.390
When you're on a mountain

784
00:31:21.390 --> 00:31:23.390
or on a hill

785
00:31:23.390 --> 00:31:25.390
and an air mass comes in,

786
00:31:25.390 --> 00:31:27.390
you can picture it:

787
00:31:27.390 --> 00:31:29.390
nice parallel lines come in,

788
00:31:29.390 --> 00:31:31.570
the wind comes in

789
00:31:31.570 --> 00:31:33.570
and then we have a hill

790
00:31:33.570 --> 00:31:35.900
where the air mass is forced to rise,

791
00:31:35.900 --> 00:31:37.920
and that leads to a narrowing

792
00:31:37.920 --> 00:31:39.920
over the hill or on the mountain ridge above,

793
00:31:39.920 --> 00:31:41.920
and so the wind speed

794
00:31:41.920 --> 00:31:44.260
on top of the mountain is at its strongest.

795
00:31:44.260 --> 00:31:46.260
So if you stand on a mountain

796
00:31:46.260 --> 00:31:48.340
and launch, or on a hill,

797
00:31:48.340 --> 00:31:50.340
and there's very strong wind,

798
00:31:50.340 --> 00:31:52.340
then descend, if you can,

799
00:31:52.340 --> 00:31:54.340
depending on what the terrain allows,

800
00:31:54.340 --> 00:31:56.340
a few hundred metres,

801
00:31:56.340 --> 00:31:58.340
and you'll notice that in the lower layer

802
00:31:58.340 --> 00:32:00.340
the wind is usually much weaker

803
00:32:00.340 --> 00:32:02.340
than right up on top,

804
00:32:02.340 --> 00:32:04.580
right in the compression.

805
00:32:04.580 --> 00:32:06.580
It's also something

806
00:32:06.580 --> 00:32:08.580
we'll perhaps look at with soaring

807
00:32:08.580 --> 00:32:10.580
in flight practice

808
00:32:10.580 --> 00:32:12.580
or that you may have already done.

809
00:32:12.580 --> 00:32:14.580
Of course what's important is

810
00:32:14.580 --> 00:32:16.580
we want to stay in exactly the zone

811
00:32:16.580 --> 00:32:18.660
where the updraft is,

812
00:32:18.660 --> 00:32:20.660
where the wind is rising.

813
00:32:20.660 --> 00:32:22.660
Leading to an acceleration of the wind,

814
00:32:22.660 --> 00:32:24.830
because of the Venturi effect.

815
00:32:24.830 --> 00:32:29.010
Right.

816
00:32:29.010 --> 00:32:31.010
So we've looked at wind systems,

817
00:32:31.010 --> 00:32:33.010
low-pressure areas, high-pressure areas.

818
00:32:33.010 --> 00:32:35.010
We've learned how to read wind from

819
00:32:35.010 --> 00:32:37.010
the isobars,

820
00:32:37.010 --> 00:32:39.060
and also how to read wind strength.

821
00:32:39.060 --> 00:32:43.140
Because the closer the isobars are together,

822
00:32:43.140 --> 00:32:45.570
the stronger the wind.

823
00:32:45.570 --> 00:32:47.570
And the further apart the isobars are —

824
00:32:47.570 --> 00:32:49.570
think of a topographic map,

825
00:32:49.570 --> 00:32:51.570
a landscape map —

826
00:32:51.570 --> 00:32:53.570
the further apart the isobars are,

827
00:32:53.570 --> 00:32:55.570
the weaker the pressure gradient,

828
00:32:55.570 --> 00:32:57.570
the weaker

829
00:32:57.570 --> 00:32:59.570
the equalizing flow between

830
00:32:59.570 --> 00:33:01.970
these pressure areas.

831
00:33:01.970 --> 00:33:03.970
It's really important that we

832
00:33:03.970 --> 00:33:05.970
piece together the various topics

833
00:33:05.970 --> 00:33:07.970
as a whole.

834
00:33:07.970 --> 00:33:09.970
The deeper your understanding becomes

835
00:33:09.970 --> 00:33:11.970
of what's happening with these air masses,

836
00:33:11.970 --> 00:33:13.970
the more you can put together.

837
00:33:13.970 --> 00:33:15.970
It's like a jigsaw puzzle,

838
00:33:15.970 --> 00:33:17.970
where one piece fits into another.

839
00:33:17.970 --> 00:33:19.970
Then flight weather

840
00:33:19.970 --> 00:33:21.970
becomes a fascinating field

841
00:33:21.970 --> 00:33:23.970
and you enjoy

842
00:33:23.970 --> 00:33:25.970
understanding the fundamentals

843
00:33:25.970 --> 00:33:27.970
and understanding the basics.

844
00:33:27.970 --> 00:33:29.970
That's why the course is important:

845
00:33:29.970 --> 00:33:31.970
so you understand the basics

846
00:33:31.970 --> 00:33:34.020
and not just memorize stuff.

847
00:33:34.020 --> 00:33:36.020
We'll go on with that

848
00:33:36.020 --> 00:33:39.280
in the next slides.

849
00:33:39.280 --> 00:33:41.280
The only topic that we

850
00:33:41.280 --> 00:33:43.280
haven't yet looked at

851
00:33:43.280 --> 00:33:45.280
on the isobar chart

852
00:33:45.280 --> 00:33:47.280
are the fronts —

853
00:33:47.280 --> 00:33:49.280
the blue, red and purple lines

854
00:33:49.280 --> 00:33:51.870
with the various symbols on them.

855
00:33:51.870 --> 00:33:53.870
These lead to special

856
00:33:53.870 --> 00:33:55.870
meteorological conditions

857
00:33:55.870 --> 00:33:57.870
which for us as paraglider pilots

858
00:33:57.870 --> 00:33:59.870
are really important

859
00:33:59.870 --> 00:34:01.870
to understand

860
00:34:01.870 --> 00:34:03.870
and to grasp the dangers of these fronts.

861
00:34:03.870 --> 00:34:07.010
But to understand fronts,

862
00:34:07.010 --> 00:34:09.010
let's go back once more

863
00:34:09.010 --> 00:34:11.010
to how a front actually forms.

864
00:34:11.010 --> 00:34:13.440
How does a front form?

865
00:34:13.440 --> 00:34:15.980
The air masses on the globe

866
00:34:15.980 --> 00:34:17.980
warm up differently.

867
00:34:17.980 --> 00:34:19.980
We have a colder air mass

868
00:34:19.980 --> 00:34:21.980
up in the polar region

869
00:34:21.980 --> 00:34:23.980
and a warmer, moist air mass

870
00:34:23.980 --> 00:34:25.980
in the tropical or subtropical region.

871
00:34:25.980 --> 00:34:28.220
And we covered earlier:

872
00:34:28.220 --> 00:34:30.220
an air mass describes

873
00:34:30.220 --> 00:34:32.220
an area, a volume of air

874
00:34:32.220 --> 00:34:34.220
that has similar properties.

875
00:34:34.220 --> 00:34:36.220
So we have two different air masses

876
00:34:36.220 --> 00:34:38.220
and in between there's an

877
00:34:38.220 --> 00:34:41.230
air-mass boundary.

878
00:34:41.230 --> 00:34:43.230
And this air-mass boundary

879
00:34:43.230 --> 00:34:45.280
is described by a front.

880
00:34:45.280 --> 00:34:47.940
We have the blue triangles,

881
00:34:47.940 --> 00:34:49.940
those describe a cold front,

882
00:34:49.940 --> 00:34:51.940
and we have the red bumps,

883
00:34:51.940 --> 00:34:53.940
so the round symbols,

884
00:34:53.940 --> 00:34:55.940
and we have the red bumps,

885
00:34:55.940 --> 00:34:57.950
those describe a warm front.

886
00:34:57.950 --> 00:34:59.950
Below there's also a mixed form,

887
00:34:59.950 --> 00:35:01.950
an occlusion, which we'll get to

888
00:35:01.950 --> 00:35:03.950
later — that's the third form

889
00:35:03.950 --> 00:35:06.350
of front that exists.

890
00:35:06.350 --> 00:35:08.350
So you can imagine,

891
00:35:08.350 --> 00:35:10.770
we have the different air masses,

892
00:35:10.770 --> 00:35:12.770
and now we have, for example,

893
00:35:12.770 --> 00:35:14.770
a low-pressure area that creates a vortex.

894
00:35:14.770 --> 00:35:16.770
Picture maybe in the extreme case

895
00:35:16.770 --> 00:35:18.770
a hurricane.

896
00:35:18.770 --> 00:35:20.780
It's like a huge vortex,

897
00:35:20.780 --> 00:35:23.020
it's a mixer that swirls the air masses

898
00:35:23.020 --> 00:35:25.020
around and so

899
00:35:25.020 --> 00:35:27.020
fronts start to form.

900
00:35:27.020 --> 00:35:29.020
An air mass might draw from the north

901
00:35:29.020 --> 00:35:31.020
toward the south, and a warmer air mass

902
00:35:31.020 --> 00:35:33.020
draws from the south toward the north,

903
00:35:33.020 --> 00:35:35.020
and accordingly a front system

904
00:35:35.020 --> 00:35:37.020
starts to move. An air mass is

905
00:35:37.020 --> 00:35:39.040
moved and accordingly

906
00:35:39.040 --> 00:35:41.280
gets exchanged.

907
00:35:41.280 --> 00:35:43.280
And so step by step

908
00:35:43.280 --> 00:35:45.520
the fronts form.

909
00:35:45.520 --> 00:35:47.520
Now you can picture this:

910
00:35:47.520 --> 00:35:49.520
we have two wind directions for the low-pressure area

911
00:35:49.520 --> 00:35:51.520
that start to rotate,

912
00:35:51.520 --> 00:35:53.520
which brings the whole system into rotation

913
00:35:53.520 --> 00:35:56.620
and accordingly

914
00:35:56.620 --> 00:36:00.850
forms these fronts.

915
00:36:00.850 --> 00:36:03.090
What you can see nicely here

916
00:36:03.090 --> 00:36:05.090
is that first

917
00:36:05.090 --> 00:36:07.090
a warm front leads the way,

918
00:36:07.090 --> 00:36:09.200
the red line,

919
00:36:09.200 --> 00:36:11.200
and we have a cold front

920
00:36:11.200 --> 00:36:13.200
that comes behind.

921
00:36:13.200 --> 00:36:15.200
We'll look at this in a moment.

922
00:36:15.200 --> 00:36:17.200
A cold front moves faster

923
00:36:17.200 --> 00:36:19.340
than a warm front.

924
00:36:19.340 --> 00:36:21.340
A cold front is almost twice as fast

925
00:36:21.340 --> 00:36:23.340
as a warm front.

926
00:36:23.340 --> 00:36:25.340
And so it happens that

927
00:36:25.340 --> 00:36:27.340
the cold front

928
00:36:27.340 --> 00:36:29.340
catches up with the warm front

929
00:36:29.340 --> 00:36:31.490
and you can see it here

930
00:36:31.490 --> 00:36:33.490
in the center of the low pressure —

931
00:36:33.490 --> 00:36:35.490
at some point occlusions form.

932
00:36:35.490 --> 00:36:37.490
An occlusion describes

933
00:36:37.490 --> 00:36:39.490
a mixed form of these two fronts.

934
00:36:39.490 --> 00:36:41.490
We'll now get into more

935
00:36:41.490 --> 00:36:43.490
detail on

936
00:36:43.490 --> 00:36:45.490
what that means and what it looks like.

937
00:36:45.490 --> 00:36:48.940
We can see here

938
00:36:48.940 --> 00:36:50.940
how the air masses rotate

939
00:36:50.940 --> 00:36:52.940
and how the various front systems

940
00:36:52.940 --> 00:36:54.940
form from the two air masses.

941
00:36:54.940 --> 00:36:57.340
Let's first look at the cold front.

942
00:36:57.340 --> 00:36:59.340
It's almost the most important front,

943
00:36:59.340 --> 00:37:01.340
or the most dangerous front,

944
00:37:01.340 --> 00:37:04.420
for paraglider pilots.

945
00:37:04.420 --> 00:37:06.420
A cold front comes in —

946
00:37:06.420 --> 00:37:08.420
you can picture this:

947
00:37:08.420 --> 00:37:10.560
in this graphic it moves from left to right.

948
00:37:10.560 --> 00:37:12.560
The cold air mass pushes

949
00:37:12.560 --> 00:37:14.560
in underneath, since it's heavier.

950
00:37:14.560 --> 00:37:16.560
So it pushes in underneath

951
00:37:16.560 --> 00:37:18.560
and it comes in

952
00:37:18.560 --> 00:37:20.560
in a teardrop shape. You can remember:

953
00:37:20.560 --> 00:37:22.560
the shape of this line

954
00:37:22.560 --> 00:37:24.560
in the vertical is a teardrop

955
00:37:24.560 --> 00:37:27.060
coming in.

956
00:37:27.060 --> 00:37:29.060
So cold air pushes in underneath.

957
00:37:29.060 --> 00:37:31.300
The warmer air is lighter

958
00:37:31.300 --> 00:37:33.300
and so it wants to rise.

959
00:37:33.300 --> 00:37:36.460
And so you get a

960
00:37:36.460 --> 00:37:38.540
large-scale

961
00:37:38.540 --> 00:37:40.540
rising of this warm,

962
00:37:40.540 --> 00:37:43.940
moist air mass.

963
00:37:43.940 --> 00:37:45.940
And clouds form in this rising process,

964
00:37:45.940 --> 00:37:47.940
which at some point rain out

965
00:37:47.940 --> 00:37:49.950
and in the extreme form

966
00:37:49.950 --> 00:37:52.030
of course produce thunderstorms.

967
00:37:52.030 --> 00:37:54.030
So with a really active cold front,

968
00:37:54.030 --> 00:37:56.030
thunderstorms always come along.

969
00:37:56.030 --> 00:37:59.020
And these thunderstorms

970
00:37:59.020 --> 00:38:01.020
of course mean very strong wind

971
00:38:01.020 --> 00:38:03.020
or very strong gusts.

972
00:38:03.020 --> 00:38:05.020
That's of course for paragliding

973
00:38:05.020 --> 00:38:07.440
extremely dangerous.

974
00:38:07.440 --> 00:38:10.510
What's a problem with the cold front,

975
00:38:10.510 --> 00:38:12.510
is that ahead of the cold front

976
00:38:12.510 --> 00:38:14.510
we usually have nice weather.

977
00:38:14.510 --> 00:38:16.620
There's sunshine,

978
00:38:16.620 --> 00:38:18.740
the weather is nice,

979
00:38:18.740 --> 00:38:20.740
it makes you want to fly.

980
00:38:20.740 --> 00:38:22.740
Maybe there's a bit of wind.

981
00:38:22.740 --> 00:38:24.740
In Switzerland it's often accompanied

982
00:38:24.740 --> 00:38:26.740
by west wind, or southwest wind,

983
00:38:26.740 --> 00:38:28.980
or a bit of Foehn,

984
00:38:28.980 --> 00:38:30.980
we'll come to that later.

985
00:38:30.980 --> 00:38:32.980
But it's usually accompanied by some wind,

986
00:38:32.980 --> 00:38:34.980
and often you also get good

987
00:38:34.980 --> 00:38:36.980
weather charts.

988
00:38:36.980 --> 00:38:39.340
Things are rising, which is basically

989
00:38:39.340 --> 00:38:41.340
what we want.

990
00:38:41.340 --> 00:38:43.340
But if on this weather chart,

991
00:38:43.340 --> 00:38:45.340
the isobar chart

992
00:38:45.340 --> 00:38:47.340
we hopefully briefly study before flying,

993
00:38:47.340 --> 00:38:49.340
we see that a cold front

994
00:38:49.340 --> 00:38:51.340
is coming in, then we really have to

995
00:38:51.340 --> 00:38:53.340
be cautious as paraglider pilots,

996
00:38:53.340 --> 00:38:55.340
because that comes with a lot of wind

997
00:38:55.340 --> 00:38:57.340
and a lot of rising

998
00:38:57.340 --> 00:38:59.340
air masses, where we really

999
00:38:59.340 --> 00:39:01.340
need to land quickly too.

1000
00:39:01.340 --> 00:39:03.340
With a cold front it's really appropriate

1001
00:39:03.340 --> 00:39:05.740
to factor in the daily timing.

1002
00:39:05.740 --> 00:39:07.740
A cold front comes in at 40 to 70 km/h,

1003
00:39:07.740 --> 00:39:10.080
so it can be relatively fast,

1004
00:39:10.080 --> 00:39:12.080
really important. The wind can of course

1005
00:39:12.080 --> 00:39:14.450
become much stronger near thunderstorms,

1006
00:39:14.450 --> 00:39:16.450
and it takes about 6 to 12 hours

1007
00:39:16.450 --> 00:39:18.450
for it to pass over Switzerland.

1008
00:39:18.450 --> 00:39:20.450
So it can sometimes be a relatively quick thing.

1009
00:39:20.450 --> 00:39:25.280
Right.

1010
00:39:25.280 --> 00:39:27.280
So be careful

1011
00:39:27.280 --> 00:39:29.580
with these cold fronts.

1012
00:39:29.580 --> 00:39:31.580
Really important: if you're flying ahead

1013
00:39:31.580 --> 00:39:33.580
of a cold front, keep

1014
00:39:33.580 --> 00:39:35.580
checking the weather radar, and especially

1015
00:39:35.580 --> 00:39:37.580
keep your eyes on the sky.

1016
00:39:37.580 --> 00:39:39.580
The thunderstorms come after,

1017
00:39:39.580 --> 00:39:41.580
and it looks roughly like this.

1018
00:39:41.580 --> 00:39:44.530
We'll also look at the topic of thunderstorms

1019
00:39:44.530 --> 00:39:46.530
in more detail in this course.

1020
00:39:46.530 --> 00:39:48.530
But here's a rule of thumb for you:

1021
00:39:48.530 --> 00:39:50.530
when thunderstorms come in a line

1022
00:39:50.530 --> 00:39:52.530
on the weather radar like it looks here,

1023
00:39:52.530 --> 00:39:54.530
it's always extremely dangerous.

1024
00:39:54.530 --> 00:39:56.530
Because then it's a really active front,

1025
00:39:56.530 --> 00:39:58.530
the thunderstorms are very strong, and

1026
00:39:58.530 --> 00:40:00.530
they really come through in a line.

1027
00:40:00.530 --> 00:40:02.530
And if you see such a thunderstorm line

1028
00:40:02.530 --> 00:40:04.530
on the weather radar, I would

1029
00:40:04.530 --> 00:40:06.530
personally land really quickly,

1030
00:40:06.530 --> 00:40:08.530
even if the thunderstorms are still 100 km away,

1031
00:40:08.530 --> 00:40:10.530
and the strong wind also gets pushed ahead.

1032
00:40:10.530 --> 00:40:12.530
And then you can get cold-air outflows

1033
00:40:12.530 --> 00:40:14.530
from the thunderstorm, which are very, very dangerous

1034
00:40:14.530 --> 00:40:16.530
for paraglider pilots,

1035
00:40:16.530 --> 00:40:18.530
which we'll look at

1036
00:40:18.530 --> 00:40:20.530
in the thunderstorm section

1037
00:40:20.530 --> 00:40:23.120
of this theory course in more detail.

1038
00:40:23.120 --> 00:40:25.840
But here about the weather radar.

1039
00:40:25.840 --> 00:40:27.840
Important on the weather radar, another practical tip:

1040
00:40:27.840 --> 00:40:29.950
don't just look at the radar,

1041
00:40:29.950 --> 00:40:31.950
but also look at the sky,

1042
00:40:31.950 --> 00:40:33.950
because the radar images are usually

1043
00:40:33.950 --> 00:40:35.950
a quarter-hour old, or even half an hour,

1044
00:40:35.950 --> 00:40:37.950
depending — make sure they're current.

1045
00:40:37.950 --> 00:40:39.950
But also look up at the sky,

1046
00:40:39.950 --> 00:40:41.950
not just at your phone when you go flying.

1047
00:40:41.950 --> 00:40:45.170
And one little addition

1048
00:40:45.170 --> 00:40:47.170
about thunderstorms.

1049
00:40:47.170 --> 00:40:49.280
The closer

1050
00:40:49.280 --> 00:40:51.280
to the center of a low-pressure area,

1051
00:40:51.280 --> 00:40:53.280
for instance — that you

1052
00:40:53.280 --> 00:40:55.280
move within this front,

1053
00:40:55.280 --> 00:40:57.280
the more active the cold front is.

1054
00:40:57.280 --> 00:40:59.280
If you're only brushed

1055
00:40:59.280 --> 00:41:01.280
by the very outermost tip of this front,

1056
00:41:01.280 --> 00:41:03.280
like here in the case of Greece,

1057
00:41:03.280 --> 00:41:05.280
it can be that the whole weather phenomenon

1058
00:41:05.280 --> 00:41:07.280
is just a bit weaker

1059
00:41:07.280 --> 00:41:09.280
and not really that bad,

1060
00:41:09.280 --> 00:41:11.280
maybe still flyable. But be careful,

1061
00:41:11.280 --> 00:41:13.280
that has a lot to do with experience.

1062
00:41:13.280 --> 00:41:15.330
But if you really get hit

1063
00:41:15.330 --> 00:41:17.330
full-on in the middle of a cold front,

1064
00:41:17.330 --> 00:41:19.410
then it's really very active

1065
00:41:19.410 --> 00:41:21.410
and then definitely no flying.

1066
00:41:21.410 --> 00:41:23.410
But if you're only brushed,

1067
00:41:23.410 --> 00:41:25.410
you can sometimes

1068
00:41:25.410 --> 00:41:27.410
still go flying

1069
00:41:27.410 --> 00:41:29.410
and it leads to a slight

1070
00:41:29.410 --> 00:41:31.410
destabilization of the air mass.

1071
00:41:31.410 --> 00:41:33.410
But that's more for advanced pilots.

1072
00:41:33.410 --> 00:41:35.410
But good to know,

1073
00:41:35.410 --> 00:41:37.410
this gradient — that a front

1074
00:41:37.410 --> 00:41:39.410
in the center is always stronger

1075
00:41:39.410 --> 00:41:41.410
than in the outermost areas of the front.

1076
00:41:41.410 --> 00:41:44.660
Then we come to the

1077
00:41:44.660 --> 00:41:46.660
second frontal phenomenon,

1078
00:41:46.660 --> 00:41:48.660
and that's the warm front.

1079
00:41:48.660 --> 00:41:51.620
With the warm front,

1080
00:41:51.620 --> 00:41:53.620
a warmer air mass,

1081
00:41:53.620 --> 00:41:55.620
as we've seen,

1082
00:41:55.620 --> 00:41:57.620
is forced to glide up onto a colder air mass.

1083
00:41:57.620 --> 00:41:59.760
With air masses it's always about

1084
00:41:59.760 --> 00:42:01.760
which one is colder or warmer.

1085
00:42:01.760 --> 00:42:03.760
It doesn't mean per se that one is warm.

1086
00:42:03.760 --> 00:42:05.760
You could have an air mass

1087
00:42:05.760 --> 00:42:07.760
at minus 20 degrees

1088
00:42:07.760 --> 00:42:09.760
and the other air mass at minus 10.

1089
00:42:09.760 --> 00:42:11.760
That's also cold, but it's colder.

1090
00:42:11.760 --> 00:42:13.760
So a warmer air mass

1091
00:42:13.760 --> 00:42:15.760
comes in.

1092
00:42:15.760 --> 00:42:17.760
And so the air mass

1093
00:42:17.760 --> 00:42:19.810
is less dense, a bit lighter,

1094
00:42:19.810 --> 00:42:21.810
and it glides up

1095
00:42:21.810 --> 00:42:23.860
on top of the cold air mass.

1096
00:42:23.860 --> 00:42:25.940
So

1097
00:42:25.940 --> 00:42:27.940
a warm front comes in in a wedge shape.

1098
00:42:27.940 --> 00:42:29.940
You can remember this:

1099
00:42:29.940 --> 00:42:31.940
the diagonal line, the air mass

1100
00:42:31.940 --> 00:42:34.530
that gets lifted, forms

1101
00:42:34.530 --> 00:42:36.800
a diagonal line.

1102
00:42:36.800 --> 00:42:38.800
This makes it for us paraglider pilots

1103
00:42:38.800 --> 00:42:40.800
much less dangerous

1104
00:42:40.800 --> 00:42:42.800
than a teardrop shape.

1105
00:42:42.800 --> 00:42:44.800
If I'm standing down here on the mountain

1106
00:42:44.800 --> 00:42:46.800
and want to fly, I see

1107
00:42:46.800 --> 00:42:48.800
a lot. Earlier, before the front

1108
00:42:48.800 --> 00:42:50.800
even reaches the ground,

1109
00:42:50.800 --> 00:42:52.800
I see high cloud layers.

1110
00:42:52.800 --> 00:42:54.910
The sky gets milkier and milkier.

1111
00:42:54.910 --> 00:42:57.020
It's not really nice

1112
00:42:57.020 --> 00:42:59.020
for flying anyway.

1113
00:42:59.020 --> 00:43:01.020
The air mass keeps coming

1114
00:43:01.020 --> 00:43:03.020
lower and lower, and then you notice

1115
00:43:03.020 --> 00:43:05.200
that it's not

1116
00:43:05.200 --> 00:43:07.200
good flying weather.

1117
00:43:07.200 --> 00:43:09.200
So the warm front is much less dangerous

1118
00:43:09.200 --> 00:43:11.200
than the cold front. But logically

1119
00:43:11.200 --> 00:43:13.200
you also wouldn't fly in a warm front.

1120
00:43:13.200 --> 00:43:15.200
Of course that's always combined with wind.

1121
00:43:15.200 --> 00:43:17.220
What you also see is

1122
00:43:17.220 --> 00:43:19.220
a warm front comes in much

1123
00:43:19.220 --> 00:43:21.220
more slowly.

1124
00:43:21.220 --> 00:43:23.220
It comes in at 15 to 25 km/h.

1125
00:43:23.220 --> 00:43:25.870
It takes 12 to 24

1126
00:43:25.870 --> 00:43:27.870
sometimes more hours

1127
00:43:27.870 --> 00:43:29.870
to pass over Switzerland.

1128
00:43:29.870 --> 00:43:31.870
That's usually a somewhat longer affair.

1129
00:43:31.870 --> 00:43:33.870
It can sometimes also be two days

1130
00:43:33.870 --> 00:43:35.870
of flying weather in a warm front.

1131
00:43:35.870 --> 00:43:37.870
And in the lead-up,

1132
00:43:37.870 --> 00:43:39.870
as already discussed, it brings high shading,

1133
00:43:39.870 --> 00:43:41.870
which weakens the thermal

1134
00:43:41.870 --> 00:43:44.110
activity and

1135
00:43:44.110 --> 00:43:46.110
doesn't really bring great flying weather.

1136
00:43:49.070 --> 00:43:51.070
With a warm front the

1137
00:43:51.070 --> 00:43:53.070
only problem there might be —

1138
00:43:53.070 --> 00:43:55.070
also for mountaineers for example —

1139
00:43:55.070 --> 00:43:57.070
is that when I'm down here,

1140
00:43:57.070 --> 00:43:59.070
I can't see through the cloud doors,

1141
00:43:59.070 --> 00:44:01.070
and see what's behind.

1142
00:44:01.070 --> 00:44:03.070
Even with a warm front, behind it

1143
00:44:03.070 --> 00:44:05.070
thunderstorms can sometimes form.

1144
00:44:05.070 --> 00:44:07.070
Especially with an occlusion,

1145
00:44:07.070 --> 00:44:09.070
which we'll get to in a moment,

1146
00:44:09.070 --> 00:44:11.070
there can be huge thunderstorm towers behind,

1147
00:44:11.070 --> 00:44:13.070
which are of course very dangerous,

1148
00:44:13.070 --> 00:44:15.070
because they bring the weather with them,

1149
00:44:15.070 --> 00:44:17.070
strong wind, heavy precipitation,

1150
00:44:17.070 --> 00:44:19.070
and you can't even see them,

1151
00:44:19.070 --> 00:44:22.110
because the cloud layers are covering everything.

1152
00:44:22.110 --> 00:44:24.110
By the way, you can see here the cloud names

1153
00:44:24.110 --> 00:44:26.110
that come with a warm front.

1154
00:44:26.110 --> 00:44:28.110
You'll have to learn those as well.

1155
00:44:28.110 --> 00:44:30.110
We'll look at the cloud names later.

1156
00:44:30.110 --> 00:44:32.450
But for you to know,

1157
00:44:32.450 --> 00:44:34.450
the warm front usually comes

1158
00:44:34.450 --> 00:44:36.450
with stratus clouds.

1159
00:44:36.450 --> 00:44:38.450
So we have cirrostratus, altostratus,

1160
00:44:38.450 --> 00:44:40.450
nimbostratus — it's always tied to stratus.

1161
00:44:40.450 --> 00:44:42.450
What stratus means

1162
00:44:42.450 --> 00:44:44.450
and what these cloud names are

1163
00:44:44.450 --> 00:44:46.450
and what they look like,

1164
00:44:46.450 --> 00:44:48.450
we'll hear in another chapter,

1165
00:44:48.450 --> 00:44:50.450
when we look at cloud names.

1166
00:44:50.450 --> 00:44:52.450
But remember:

1167
00:44:52.450 --> 00:44:54.450
cirrostratus, altostratus, nimbostratus

1168
00:44:54.450 --> 00:44:56.450
will very likely be

1169
00:44:56.450 --> 00:44:58.450
asked on the theory exam.

1170
00:44:58.450 --> 00:45:00.450
When these cloud forms appear,

1171
00:45:00.450 --> 00:45:02.450
you can already start to think

1172
00:45:02.450 --> 00:45:04.560
of a warm front in the back of your mind.

1173
00:45:04.560 --> 00:45:08.800
Here are the pictures

1174
00:45:08.800 --> 00:45:10.800
of how it comes in.

1175
00:45:10.800 --> 00:45:12.800
The clouds look like this,

1176
00:45:12.800 --> 00:45:14.800
they are layered clouds.

1177
00:45:14.800 --> 00:45:16.800
These are the cloud decks

1178
00:45:16.800 --> 00:45:18.800
that come lower and lower

1179
00:45:18.800 --> 00:45:20.880
as the front progresses.

1180
00:45:20.880 --> 00:45:22.880
And that's roughly what these cloud forms look like.

1181
00:45:22.880 --> 00:45:29.360
Then we come

1182
00:45:29.360 --> 00:45:31.410
to the chapter on occlusions.

1183
00:45:31.410 --> 00:45:33.460
Occlusions —

1184
00:45:33.460 --> 00:45:35.460
you don't actually need to know

1185
00:45:35.460 --> 00:45:37.460
extremely much about them.

1186
00:45:37.460 --> 00:45:39.460
But it does still come up on the theory exam.

1187
00:45:39.460 --> 00:45:41.460
It's a mixed form of these two fronts.

1188
00:45:41.460 --> 00:45:43.730
And as discussed,

1189
00:45:43.730 --> 00:45:45.730
what's relevant for us

1190
00:45:45.730 --> 00:45:47.730
in practice is mainly that

1191
00:45:47.730 --> 00:45:49.730
with an occlusion the sky

1192
00:45:49.730 --> 00:45:51.730
is often covered

1193
00:45:51.730 --> 00:45:53.730
and there are what's called masked thunderstorms.

1194
00:45:53.730 --> 00:45:55.730
Those are thunderstorm towers behind it,

1195
00:45:55.730 --> 00:45:57.730
because the warm front gets caught up.

1196
00:45:57.730 --> 00:45:59.730
It's faster.

1197
00:45:59.730 --> 00:46:01.730
There can be thunderstorms behind.

1198
00:46:01.730 --> 00:46:03.730
But if we're up front,

1199
00:46:03.730 --> 00:46:05.730
we maybe don't even see the thunderstorm towers.

1200
00:46:05.730 --> 00:46:08.380
And that's really important for us

1201
00:46:08.380 --> 00:46:10.380
to know that this can happen.

1202
00:46:10.380 --> 00:46:12.380
A very detailed question

1203
00:46:12.380 --> 00:46:14.690
that doesn't have a whole lot to do with flight practice

1204
00:46:14.690 --> 00:46:16.690
or that for most paraglider pilots

1205
00:46:16.690 --> 00:46:18.690
isn't of much relevance,

1206
00:46:18.690 --> 00:46:20.690
is the character of occlusions.

1207
00:46:20.690 --> 00:46:22.690
That also comes up on the exam.

1208
00:46:22.690 --> 00:46:24.690
There's what's called an occlusion

1209
00:46:24.690 --> 00:46:26.690
with cold-front character

1210
00:46:26.690 --> 00:46:28.690
and an occlusion

1211
00:46:28.690 --> 00:46:30.690
with warm-front character.

1212
00:46:30.690 --> 00:46:32.690
So when you see an occlusion image

1213
00:46:32.690 --> 00:46:34.690
with the two dividing lines

1214
00:46:34.690 --> 00:46:36.690
of the air masses,

1215
00:46:36.690 --> 00:46:38.690
just check which dividing line touches the ground.

1216
00:46:38.690 --> 00:46:40.740
Accordingly,

1217
00:46:40.740 --> 00:46:42.780
in this case the line

1218
00:46:42.780 --> 00:46:44.780
of the cold front touches the ground

1219
00:46:44.780 --> 00:46:46.780
and in the other case

1220
00:46:46.780 --> 00:46:48.780
the line of

1221
00:46:48.780 --> 00:46:50.780
the warm front touches the ground —

1222
00:46:50.780 --> 00:46:53.340
with cold-front character and warm-front character.

1223
00:46:53.340 --> 00:46:55.340
Up here in this graphic you see

1224
00:46:55.340 --> 00:46:57.840
a cold-front character.

1225
00:46:57.840 --> 00:47:00.270
You need to learn that for the theory exam.

1226
00:47:00.270 --> 00:47:02.270
But it's not really that relevant

1227
00:47:02.270 --> 00:47:04.270
what the differences are

1228
00:47:04.270 --> 00:47:08.720
for normal pilots.

1229
00:47:08.720 --> 00:47:12.140
Here I'd like to very briefly

1230
00:47:12.140 --> 00:47:14.140
summarize a few tips.

1231
00:47:14.140 --> 00:47:16.140
These are the two charts

1232
00:47:16.140 --> 00:47:18.160
that come up most on the theory exam.

1233
00:47:18.160 --> 00:47:20.160
Maybe on the left chart, summarized once more

1234
00:47:20.160 --> 00:47:22.160
as a recap.

1235
00:47:22.160 --> 00:47:24.160
We have different pressure areas.

1236
00:47:24.160 --> 00:47:26.160
Think about: where is the low pressure?

1237
00:47:26.160 --> 00:47:28.160
Where is the high pressure?

1238
00:47:28.160 --> 00:47:30.160
How do the air masses rotate accordingly?

1239
00:47:30.160 --> 00:47:32.160
High pressure clockwise,

1240
00:47:32.160 --> 00:47:34.160
low pressure counterclockwise.

1241
00:47:34.160 --> 00:47:36.180
Then you've got the wind direction.

1242
00:47:36.180 --> 00:47:38.180
Picture the compass rose.

1243
00:47:38.180 --> 00:47:40.180
Which direction is the wind coming from?

1244
00:47:40.180 --> 00:47:42.180
Degrees accordingly.

1245
00:47:42.180 --> 00:47:44.180
When the isobar lines are close together,

1246
00:47:44.180 --> 00:47:46.180
we have very strong wind,

1247
00:47:46.180 --> 00:47:48.180
as in this case in Stockholm.

1248
00:47:48.180 --> 00:47:50.180
If they're far apart,

1249
00:47:50.180 --> 00:47:52.180
we have relatively weak wind.

1250
00:47:52.180 --> 00:47:54.220
I sometimes use Switzerland as an example.

1251
00:47:54.220 --> 00:47:56.220
If the isobars,

1252
00:47:56.220 --> 00:47:58.220
taking Switzerland's size,

1253
00:47:58.220 --> 00:48:00.340
are equally close together,

1254
00:48:00.340 --> 00:48:02.340
important at 5 hPa intervals,

1255
00:48:02.340 --> 00:48:04.340
then we have relatively strong wind.

1256
00:48:04.340 --> 00:48:06.340
Once the isobars are further apart,

1257
00:48:06.340 --> 00:48:08.340
like maybe twice

1258
00:48:08.340 --> 00:48:10.340
or three times as wide as Switzerland,

1259
00:48:10.340 --> 00:48:12.340
then we have really weak winds.

1260
00:48:12.340 --> 00:48:14.340
So here in the Mediterranean region

1261
00:48:14.340 --> 00:48:16.340
we have a very low-wind area,

1262
00:48:16.340 --> 00:48:18.340
and also in the center of the high pressure relatively low wind.

1263
00:48:18.340 --> 00:48:20.960
So that's for reading wind direction

1264
00:48:20.960 --> 00:48:22.960
and wind strength.

1265
00:48:22.960 --> 00:48:24.960
Then you'll be asked using this chart.

1266
00:48:24.960 --> 00:48:28.060
Then we have the two charts here.

1267
00:48:28.060 --> 00:48:30.060
Here you see the fronts as well.

1268
00:48:30.060 --> 00:48:32.060
For this you mainly need to know

1269
00:48:32.060 --> 00:48:34.060
what cloud forms

1270
00:48:34.060 --> 00:48:36.060
come with the fronts.

1271
00:48:36.060 --> 00:48:38.060
Here we have for sure

1272
00:48:38.060 --> 00:48:40.060
thunderstorms in the cold front.

1273
00:48:40.060 --> 00:48:42.060
We might have

1274
00:48:42.060 --> 00:48:44.060
a bit of cumulus clouds ahead.

1275
00:48:44.060 --> 00:48:46.110
And here,

1276
00:48:46.110 --> 00:48:48.110
sorry, I just made a mistake.

1277
00:48:48.110 --> 00:48:50.110
We have here a cold front —

1278
00:48:50.110 --> 00:48:52.110
the triangles are really important.

1279
00:48:52.110 --> 00:48:54.110
The shapes of the symbols are important.

1280
00:48:54.110 --> 00:48:56.110
So we have triangles here,

1281
00:48:56.110 --> 00:48:58.110
that's a cold front.

1282
00:48:58.110 --> 00:49:00.110
Thunderstorms are definitely a topic here.

1283
00:49:00.110 --> 00:49:02.110
And here we have a warm front,

1284
00:49:02.110 --> 00:49:04.110
leading the way with these round symbols.

1285
00:49:04.110 --> 00:49:06.110
So accordingly we have

1286
00:49:06.110 --> 00:49:08.290
the stratus clouds, as we just discussed.

1287
00:49:08.290 --> 00:49:10.290
And we have a high pressure and a low pressure.

1288
00:49:10.290 --> 00:49:12.290
Of course in the low pressure

1289
00:49:12.290 --> 00:49:14.780
with these sharper lines,

1290
00:49:14.780 --> 00:49:16.780
it's always about precipitation.

1291
00:49:16.780 --> 00:49:18.800
Here it's certainly raining up in Stockholm.

1292
00:49:18.800 --> 00:49:20.800
And for example in Athens

1293
00:49:20.800 --> 00:49:23.460
we have high-pressure influence

1294
00:49:23.460 --> 00:49:25.460
with nice weather.

1295
00:49:25.460 --> 00:49:27.460
There's a multiple-choice learning tool

1296
00:49:27.460 --> 00:49:29.860
that you can click through.

1297
00:49:29.860 --> 00:49:31.870
And you keep being reminded

1298
00:49:31.870 --> 00:49:33.870
of the basic principles

1299
00:49:33.870 --> 00:49:35.870
that we just discussed,

1300
00:49:35.870 --> 00:49:38.180
with these two charts.

1301
00:49:38.180 --> 00:49:40.180
Then you'll be well prepared

1302
00:49:40.180 --> 00:49:42.180
for the exam,

1303
00:49:42.180 --> 00:49:46.240
as far as isobar charts and fronts go.

1304
00:49:46.240 --> 00:49:48.350
Then we come to a huge topic

1305
00:49:48.350 --> 00:49:50.350
that's important

1306
00:49:50.350 --> 00:49:52.350
to understand in depth

1307
00:49:52.350 --> 00:49:54.350
if you really want to fly paragliders well,

1308
00:49:54.350 --> 00:49:56.350
if you want to fly cross-country,

1309
00:49:56.350 --> 00:49:58.350
and that's thermals.

1310
00:49:58.350 --> 00:50:00.750
I'd suggest

1311
00:50:00.750 --> 00:50:02.750
we take a quick break,

1312
00:50:02.750 --> 00:50:04.750
so you can have something to drink,

1313
00:50:04.750 --> 00:50:06.750
and clear your head.

1314
00:50:06.750 --> 00:50:08.750
The course still goes on for a long time —

1315
00:50:08.750 --> 00:50:10.750
we have a lot more to discuss.

1316
00:50:10.750 --> 00:50:12.750
So that would maybe be a moment,

1317
00:50:12.750 --> 00:50:14.750
when we start the next chapter.
